ch.ecma.csta.callcontrol

Class CallControlAdapter

  • java.lang.Object
    • ch.ecma.csta.callcontrol.CallControlAdapter
  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    CallControlListener, java.util.EventListener

    public class CallControlAdapter
extends java.lang.Object
implements CallControlListener
    Implements a "do nothing" callback method for each call control event type. To learn more about how to use a listener adapter, see Using Listeners in the Device, Media & Call Control (DMCC) API.
    Version:
    4.1
    Author:
    Avaya Inc.

      • callCleared

        public void callCleared(CallClearedEvent event)
        Description copied from interface: CallControlListener
        A callback function which is automatically invoked on a listener previously added to a call when the CallClearedEvent occurs for that call.

        The CallClearedEvent is provided for calls that are being call-type monitored. This event indicates that a call has been cleared and no longer exists within the switching sub-domain. See CallClearedEvent for more information.

        Optional parameters are available in the private data area with an Avaya-specified CallClearedEventPrivateData object.

        Example: 

          // get the connection id of the cleared call
  ConnectionID connId = event.getClearedCall();

  // get the deviceId
  LocalDeviceID localDeviceId = connId.getDeviceID();
  DeviceID deviceID = localDeviceID.getStaticID();
 
  // cause of the event
  EventCause cause = event.getCause();
  
  // get the private data from the event
  if (event.getExtensions() != null {
      Object privDataObject = event.getExtensions().getSinglePrivateData();
      if (privDataObject instanceof CallClearedEventPrivateData) {
          CallClearReason reason = (CallClearedEventPrivateData)privDataObject.getReason();
      }
  }
        Specified by:
        callCleared in interface CallControlListener
        Parameters:
        event - provides data about a cleared call

      • conferenced

        public void conferenced(ConferencedEvent event)
        Description copied from interface: CallControlListener
        A callback function which is automatically invoked on a listener previously added to a device when the ConferencedEvent occurs on that device.

        The ConferencedEvent indicates that the conferencing device has conferenced itself or another device with an existing call and that no devices have been removed from the resulting call. See ConferencedEvent for more information.

        Optional parameters are available in the private data area with an Avaya-specified ConferencedEventPrivateData object.

        The conferencingDevice and addedParty parameters of the ConferencedEvent structure are of type SubjectDeviceID so extracting the device ID is a two-step process: 

         SubjectDeviceID subjDeviceID = event.getConferencingDevice();
 DeviceID deviceID = subjDeviceID.getDeviceIdentifier();
        Example: 
         // connection of the primary call
 ConnectionID primaryCallConnId = event.getPrimaryOldCall();
 // connection of the secondary call
 ConnectionID secondaryCallConnId = event.getSecondaryOldCall();
 // device id of the conferencing device
 DeviceID deviceID = event.getConferencingDevice().getDeviceIdentifier();
 // last device added to call
 DeviceID addedParty = event.getAddedParty.getDeviceIdentifier();
 
 // information on each device/ConnectionID in the resulting conference call
 ConnectionList connList = event.getConferenceConnections();
 ConnectionListItem[] connListItems = connList.getConnectionListItem();
 for (ConnectionListItem connItem:connListItems) {                  
     // trunk info
     AssociatedNID aNid = connItem.getAssociatedNID();
     DeviceID trunkData = aNid.getDeviceID();
     // content format: TRUNKGROUP#TRUNKMEMBER
     String trunkContent = trunkData.getContent();
 } 
 // Reason for the event
 EventCause eventCause = event.getCause();
 // local connection state of the device
 LocalConnectionState connState = event.getLocalConnectionInfo();
 
 // get the private data from the event
 if (event.getExtensions() != null {
     Object privDataObject = event.getExtensions().getSinglePrivateData();
     if (privDataObject instanceof ConferencedEventPrivateData) {
         // distributing VDN
         SubjectDeviceID vdn = (ConferencedEventPrivateData)privDataObject.getDistributingVDN();
         // Original Call Information
         OriginalCallInfo oci = (ConferencedEventPrivateData)privDataObject.getOriginalCallInfo();
         // get the trunk group and trunk member for each party on the conference
         TrunkInterfaceInfoList trunkList = (ConferencedEventPrivateData)privDataObject.getTrunkList();
         for (TrunkInterfaceInfoItem trunkItem:trunkList.getTrunkInterfaceInfoItem()){
             ConnectionID connId = trunkItem.getConnection_asn();
             String trunkGroup = trunkItem.getTrunkGroup();
             String trunkMbr = trunkItem.getTrunkMember();  
             
             // do something with the trunk and connection data
         }
     }
 }
        Specified by:
        conferenced in interface CallControlListener
        Parameters:
        event - provides data about a conference to the device

      • delivered

        public void delivered(DeliveredEvent event)
        Description copied from interface: CallControlListener
        A callback function which is automatically invoked on a listener previously added to a device when the DeliveredEvent occurs on that device.

        The DeliveredEvent indicates that a call is being presented to a device in either the Ringing or Entering Distribution modes of the alerting state. See DeliveredEvent for more information.

        Optional parameters are available in the private data area with an Avaya-specified DeliveredEventPrivateData object.

        The alertingDevice parameter of the DeliveredEvent structure is of type SubjectDeviceID so extracting the device ID is a two-step process: 

         SubjectDeviceID subjDeviceID = event.getAlertingDevice();
 DeviceID deviceID = subjDeviceID.getDeviceIdentifier();
        Example: 
          // connection that is alerting
 ConnectionID alertingConnId = event.getConnection();
 // device that is alerting 
 DeviceID alertingDeviceId = event.getAlertingDevice().getDeviceIdentifier;
 // callingDevice
 CallingDeviceID callingDeviceId = event.getCallingDevice();
 // originally calledDevice
 CalledDeviceID calledDeviceId = event.getCalledDevice();
 // previously known redirected from device
 RedirectionDeviceID redirectDeviceId = event.getLastRedirectionDevice();     
 // local connection state of the device
 LocalConnectionState connState = event.getLocalConnectionInfo(); 
 // Reason for the event
 EventCause eventCause = event.getCause();
 
 // get the private data from the event
 if (event.getExtensions() != null {
     Object privDataObject = event.getExtensions().getSinglePrivateData();
     if (privDataObject instanceof DeliveredEventPrivateData) {
         // distributing VDN
         SubjectDeviceID vdn = (DeliveredEventPrivateData)privDataObject.getDistributingVDN();
         
         // Original Call Information
         OriginalCallInfo oci = (DeliveredEventPrivateData)privDataObject.getOriginalCallInfo();
     }
 }
        Specified by:

      • failed

        public void failed(FailedEvent event)
        Description copied from interface: CallControlListener
        A callback function which is automatically invoked on a listener previously added to a device when the FailedEvent occurs on that device.

        The FailedEvent is usually generated if an outbound call (MakeCall) fails to connect for a variety of reasons (busy, no answer, reorder tone etc). See FailedEvent for more information.

        The failingDevice parameter of the FailedEvent structure is of type SubjectDeviceID so extracting the device ID is a two-step process: 

         SubjectDeviceID subjDeviceID = event.getFailingDevice();
 DeviceID deviceID = subjDeviceID.getDeviceIdentifier();
        Example: 
          // connection that failed
 ConnectionID failedConnId = event.getFailedConnection();
 // device that failed
 DeviceID failingDeviceId = event.getFailingDevice().getDeviceIdentifier;
 // callingDevice
 CallingDeviceID callingDeviceId = event.getCallingDevice();
 // originally calledDevice
 CalledDeviceID calledDeviceId = event.getCalledDevice();
 // lastRedirectionDevice = always 'not known'
 RedirectionDeviceID redirectDeviceId = event.getLastRedirectionDevice();     
 // local connection state of the device
 LocalConnectionState connState = event.getLocalConnectionInfo(); 
 // Reason for the event
 EventCause eventCause = event.getCause();

      • networkReached

        public void networkReached(NetworkReachedEvent event)
        Description copied from interface: CallControlListener
        Supported in AES 6.1 and later.

        A callback function which is automatically invoked on a listener previously added to a device when the NetworkReachedEvent occurs on that device.

        The NetworkReachedEvent indicates that a call has cut through the switching sub-domain boundary to another network; that is, has reached and engaged a Network Interface Device (e.g., trunk, CO Line). See NetworkReachedEvent for more information.

        Optional parameters are available in the private data area with an Avaya-specified NetworkReachedEventPrivateData object.

        Example: 

         // get the trunk group and trunk member used to leave the switch and enter the network
 // the trunk group and trunk member are in the DeviceID content 
 // in the format of TrunkGroupNumber#TrunkMember
 String trunkGroupAndMember = event.getNetworkInterfaceUsed().getDeviceIdentifier().getContent();
  
 // outbound connection for the call that is leaving switching sub-domain
 ConnectionID connId = event.getOutboundConnection();
 // called device
 CalledDeviceID calledDevId = event3.getCalledDevice();     
 // local connection state of the device
 LocalConnectionState connState = event.getLocalConnectionInfo(); 
 // Reason for the event
 EventCause eventCause = event.getCause();
        Specified by:
        networkReached in interface CallControlListener
        Parameters:
        event - provides data about the call that has left the switching sub-domain.

      • enteredDigits

        public void enteredDigits(EnteredDigitsEvent event)
        Description copied from interface: CallControlListener
        Supported in AES 6.1 and later.

        The EnteredDigitsEvent is a private event supported in CallControlPrivateEvents filter.

        A callback function which is automatically invoked on a listener previously added to a device when the EnteredDigitsEvent occurs on that device.

        The EnteredDigitsEvent is sent when a DTMF tone detector attached to a call and DTMF tones are received. The tone detector is disconnected when the far end answers or "#" is detected. The digits reported include: 0-9, "*", and "#". The digit string includes the "#", if present. Up to 24 digits can be entered. See EnteredDigitsEvent for more information.

        Example: 

          // connection at which the EnteredDigitsEvent was sent
 ConnectionID connId = event.getConnection();
 // get the digits that were entered
 String digits = event.getDigits();     
 // local connection state of the device
 LocalConnectionState connState = event.getLocalConnectionInfo(); 
 // Reason for the event
 EventCause eventCause = event.getCause();
        Specified by:
        enteredDigits in interface CallControlListener
        Parameters:
        event - provides entered digits for the call
